        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Then each choice of P, Q corresponds to equating P(X) + Q(X)i with the product of some n factors on the right, in which we choose exactly of the two fac- tors for each j = 0, . . ., n − 1. (We must take exactly n factors because as a polynomial in X with complex co- efficients, P(X) + Q(X)i has degree exactly n. We must choose one for each j to ensure that P(X) + Q(X)i and P(X) − Q(X)i are complex conjugates, so that P, Q have real coefficients.) Thus there are 2n such pairs; multi- plying by 2 to allow P to have leading coefficient –1 yields the desired result.",
